title: For Sale:  Unique, "Type G" Beretta Px4 Storm compact 9mm - LNIB w/3 mags
postcontent:
This low-round-count carry gun comes with THREE 15-round mags, and was converted to Type G from Type F.  This means the right side slide release lever is gone, the left side release is much narrower and the "batwing" safety levers are now flush and act as a decocker.  

I think Beretta's are under appreciated due to perceived "bulk" and the slide mounted safety.  The Type G conversion goes a long way in addressing those concerns.  I have also found that the rotating barrel concept does work well in reducing felt recoil, which helps make this gun highly accurate.  It's hard to describe the feeling as the the trigger releases the hammer; I can only say it's like "butter."

I had made the conversion as I was intending this to be my EDC.  However, I already have several other options (mainly far more expensive ones) and simply chose this as the most expendable.  Bottom line is gun still looks new (I have had it for less than three months).  250 rounds through at most.  Gun will remain a safe queen until sold.  

I am selling vs. trading.  The price is extremely fair as I don't wish to play games.

Again, this Type G makes it much better for carry and having 15+1 capacity is great.   

Illinois law will be followed for in-state transfer or I can ship FFL to FFL for $35 to anywhere in conus.  Box and all papers, manual, etc. are included.

postcontent: When the U.S. entered WW1, it had a need for rifles. The Springfield Armory had delivered approximately 843,000 M1903 rifles, but due to the difficulties in production, rather than re-tool the Pattern 14 factories to produce the standard U.S. rifle, the M1903 Springfield, it was realized that it would be much quicker to adapt the British design for the U.S. .30-06 cartridge, for which it was well-suited. postcontent:
I have a Universal M1 carbine (first gen, I believe- thin trigger group, so it'll fit in USGI pattern stocks) that's done nothing but collect dust due to ammo scarcity. I've put maybe 40 rounds through it, with one failure to extract out of the bunch that I've chalked up to using old ammo.

It lacks the bayonet lug integral to the front barrel band, and the rear sight is damaged and needs to be replaced. A small bit of work is needed to the heatshield to extend the metal tab that engages with the receiver to actually hold it on. It also lacks the oiler or any sort of accessory components. This is all stuff I could have fixed in a weekend with less than $100, but I've been too caught up in messing with ARs and AKs.

I will sell if the offer is right, but the cash offer will probably be more than the gun is worth in it's present state. I'd much rather trade it for something else interesting to someone who will show the gun a little more love than I've been- despite it's being a post-war reproduction, it'd still make a pretty gun with some effort.

The gun will come with a mostly-depleted box of Prvi Partisan .30 carbine (I believe it has 25 rounds left in) and a 30 round magazine that appears to be new production.
